<subSubSection lastPageId="264" lastPageNumber="265" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="263.[140,1108,1328,1637]" pageId="263" pageNumber="264">
Medium-sized (
<quantity box="[320,451,1363,1390]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" unit="mm" value="40.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="30.0">30–50 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths. Most are gray or brown, but also included are the beautiful green species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grote" authorityYear="1874" box="[732,807,1399,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Feralia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[732,807,1399,1425]" italics="true" pageId="263" pageNumber="264">Feralia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the colorful stiriines. The larvae feed on the leaves of trees and shrubs (Amphyrini and Psaphidini) or herbaceous plants, particularly 
<taxonomicName box="[457,574,1469,1495]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Poole" baseAuthorityYear="1995" box="[590,675,1469,1496]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Stiriini">Stiriini</taxonomicName>
). The group has undergone several reorganizations (
<bibRefCitation author="Poole RW" box="[305,437,1504,1531]" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" refId="ref262019" refString="Poole RW (1995) Noctuoidea: Noctuidae: Cuculliinae, Stiriinae, Psaphidinae (part). Fasc. 26.1. In: Dominick RB, Ferguson DC, Franclemont JG, Hodges RW, Munroe EG (Eds) The moths of America north of Mexico. Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, Washington, D. C., 249 pp." type="book" year="1995">
<collectingRegion box="[305,369,1504,1530]" country="United Kingdom" name="Poole" pageId="263" pageNumber="264">Poole</collectingRegion>
1995
</bibRefCitation>
; Kitching and Rawlins 1999; 
<bibRefCitation author="Fibiger M &amp; Lafontaine JD" box="[776,1103,1504,1531]" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" pagination="7 - 690" refId="ref244973" refString="Fibiger M, Lafontaine JD (2005) A review of the higher classification of the Noctuidae (Lepidoptera) with special reference to the holarctic fauna. Esperiana 11: 7 - 690." type="journal article" year="2005">Fibiger and Lafontaine 2005</bibRefCitation>
; Lafontaine and Schmidt in press) and now includes the Psaphidini, which until very recently (
<bibRefCitation author="Wagner DL &amp; Lafontaine JD &amp; McFarland N &amp; Connolly BA" box="[244,464,1575,1601]" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" pagination="40 - 51" refId="ref269357" refString="Wagner DL, Lafontaine JD, McFarland N, Connolly BA (2008) Early stages of Miracavira brillians (Barnes) and reassignment of the genus to the Amphipyrinae: Psaphidini: Feraliina (Noctuidae). Journal of the Lepidopterists' Society 62: 40 - 51." type="journal article" year="2008">Wagner et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
) was considered a separate subfamily, as were the 
<taxonomicName authority="(Poole 1995)" baseAuthorityName="Poole" baseAuthorityYear="1995" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Stiriini">
Stiriini (
<bibRefCitation author="Poole RW" box="[147,281,1610,1637]" pageId="263" pageNumber="264" refId="ref262019" refString="Poole RW (1995) Noctuoidea: Noctuidae: Cuculliinae, Stiriinae, Psaphidinae (part). Fasc. 26.1. In: Dominick RB, Ferguson DC, Franclemont JG, Hodges RW, Munroe EG (Eds) The moths of America north of Mexico. Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, Washington, D. C., 249 pp." type="book" year="1995">Poole 1995</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="264.[140,1107,167,228]" box="[185,1107,167,193]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">
The family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Guenee" authorityYear="1837" box="[317,480,167,193]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="264" pageNumber="265" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Amphipyrinae">Amphipyrinae</taxonomicName>
is Holarctic in distribution, with about 220 species in
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="264.[140,1107,167,228]" box="[140,784,202,228]" pageId="264" pageNumber="265">North America. Eleven species in six genera occur in AB.</paragraph>
